The AES Alamitos primarily uses the hazard and operability (HAZOP) analysis technique to perform these evaluations. HAZOP analysis in recognized as one of the most systematic and thorough hazard evaluation techniques. A team of people who have operating and maintenance experience as well as engineering expertise conducts the analyses. This team identifies and evaluates hazards of the process as well accident prevention and mitigation measures. The team makes suggestions for additional prevention and/or mitigation measures when the team believes such measures are necessary.  

The PHA team's findings are forwarded to facility management for resolution. Implementation of mitigation options in response to PHA findings is based on a relative risk ranking assigned by the PHA team. The ranking helps ensure that potential accident scenarios assigned the highest risk receive immediate attention. All approved mitigation options are tracked until they are completed. The final resolution of each finding is documented and retained.

To help ensure that the process controls and/or process hazards do not eventually deviate significantly from original design safety features, AES Alamitos, as part of the five year resubmittal process,  reviews (and if necessary) updates and revalidates the hazard analysis results.  Documentation of all PHAs conducted is maintained for inspection at the facility.

OPERATING PROCEDURES
The AES Alamitos facility maintains written procedures that address various modes of SCR system (including storage tanks) operations.  These procedures generally include:
¿	Unit start up (boiler and flue gas blower) and operation;
¿	SCR system normal start-up, normal shut down and emergency shutdown;
¿	SCR system on-line operational procedures;
¿	Aqueous ammonia ordering and truck unloading procedure.

